description:
Hotel California ist ein Lied der kalifornischen Band Eagles. Es erschien 1976! Hier ist es ein 3 Sterne Hotel in der Altstadt von Zürich. 

"Hotel California" is the title song from the Eagles' album of the same name and was released as a single in February 1977. Here it is a 3 star Hotel in the historic center of Zurich.

Foto: 7. März 2012

description:
ㄚ~不就是一台靜靜停靠在Münsterbrücke橋旁的摩托車而已，也不知偶納時在多愁善感什麼......(掩面)

或許只因為夕陽放射的光芒，穿越了聖母大教堂照耀在這一隅，當轉過身的那一剎那，看到這一幕，就不自覺的按下快門了~

@ Limmatquai / Münsterbrücke, Zürich, Switzerland 瑞士

碎碎念時間:
這裡大概是多數朋友拜訪蘇黎世最可能停留的地方，除了照片遠方巷子裡的班霍夫大道(就台灣最常見到的中正路啦，SHOPPING必去的地方，有沒有看到照片中的人一臉買得心滿意足的樣子)，還有眼前這條Münsterbrücke橋，就銜接了蘇黎世三大主要教堂其中的兩座，一為畫面中對岸那座蘇黎世聖母大教堂（Fraumünster）(逆光啦，黑黑的那座塔)，還有拍這張照片背後的蘇黎世大教堂（Grossmünster），算是這個都市必訪的名勝所在。
對面的這座蘇黎世聖母大教堂（Fraumünster）是蘇黎世的一座歸正會教堂，創立於853年，國王捐建了這座本篤會修女院，其土地免除賦稅，並直接受其管理。算算也有一千多年的歷史了，主要就是修女修道的地方~

description:
Photo André Knoerr, Genève. Reproduction autorisée avec mention de la source.

En 2015, des locomotives Re 4/4" assurent encore la traction de trains internationaux "classiques" et composées le plus fréquemment de voitures EC des CFF.
La Re 421 371 de la division Cargo mènera jusqu'à Lindau Hbf un EC Zürich HB - München Hbf. La division voyageurs des CFF loue contractuellement des Re 421 Cargo équipées pour circuler selon les normes de signalisation et caténaire entre St. Margrethen (CH)- Bregenz (A) et Lindau (D).
La Re 4/4" 11122 est en tête d'un IC Zürich HB - Stuttgart Hbf qu'elle tractera jusqu'à Singen Htw. (D).

description:
Zurich Bahnhofstrasse and Paradeplatz (home to the Swiss banks Credit Suisse and UBS and several Zurich prime shops) remain a no-go-area for participants of the official labour day rally at Bürkiplatz (the far end of Bahnhofstrasse, at lake Zurich). 
Zurich metro police blocks all passages to Bahnhofstrasse and Paradeplatz. Phalanx like single and double rows of officers in riot gear span across the streets. Facing Bürkliplatz, a mobile water cannon is in position on Bahnhofstrasse.

Zurich May Day, 2010

description:
Two weeks ago I spent the day in Zürich. The sun showed itself from its best side, so that I could make a few wonderful photos including also the sunset over Zürich. But that very special event took place on this river called „Limmat“. 

Imagine … here is held every year at this season a fun swimming. It is called the „Samichlausschwimmen“ in Swiss German and I would say it means something like „Santa Claus Swimming“ :-) Well, about 330 people dared at temperatures of 6 degrees (water) and 3 degrees (air) to take a swim in the river Limmat. And unlike last year, this time no snow fell ;-))

And there they stood all the swimmer and waited for their turn to jump into this river. Some of them even dressed up as Santa Claus and jumped with a loud „Ho ho ho!“ into the cold water, only to emerge with a cry (I think this water was very cold this year) (lol). It was really a magnificent spectacle :-)

Well, maybe you want to see how this event looked like? That’s why I have posted two additional images! To see them just klick on the link below to show all comments. I have posted the two images in the first two comments. I hope you like it :-)

I want to thank all very much for your "views", "Comments" and "Favourites" :-) The only thing that matters is that you have joy in this photo. Again, thank you :-)

description:
It's a bit disorientating to enter the marvelous gothic Fraumünster - once dedicated to Our Lady - in Zurich. The Benedictine convent of which it was part was founded in 853 by Ludwig II the German (806-876) for his daughter Hildegard (828-ca.856). The original chapel was rebuilt in this magnificent gothic style in 1250. And it must have been an amazing sight in its heyday. But then came Ulrich Zwingli (1484-1531), the reformer of Switzerland, who had the convent 'dissolved' in 1524. The church was stripped of Catholic, colorful furnishings and remade into a strictly Protestant house of worship. There is of course no altar now, but the choir has those famous Marc Chagall (1887-1985) stained-glass windows which draw in the crowds.
Chagall's Modernism is off-set, though, by the stunning Neo-classicist organ exactly opposite. It was built in 1953 by Orgelbau Genève and is the largest organ of Canton Zurich, with some 5793 pipes. I'd have liked to hear it but my time here was too short...
It seems to me the high-vaulted Gothic Fraumünster is not really well balanced with that Modernism on the left as you enter and Neo-classicism right. But it's food for thought about the remnants which the transitions of history leave behind...
This photo was taken as I was standing on the very place where there was once the main altar.

description: Stadler's new high-speed train for the Gotthard route, on its first passenger journey from Zurich to Erstfeld. The train is used since May 13 between Zurich and Basel with passengers, where you can try it. The first trains are also needed for test drives and training so the following schedule is not guaranteed: IR 36 Basel SBB ab/dep. 10:37 – Zürich Flughafen an/arr. 12:04 (IR 2067) IR 36 Zürich Flughafen ab/dep. 12:56 – Basel SBB an/arr. 14:24 (IR 2072) IR 37 Basel SBB ab/dep. 19:43 – Zürich HB an/arr. 20:52 (IR 2285) IR 37 Zürich HB ab/dep. 21:08 – Basel SBB an/arr. 22:13 (IR 2284) 29 of these trains, each with 405 seats, have been ordered, and 3 have been handed over to SBB so far. It can be operated with 15 kV/16.7 Hz, 25 kV/50 Hz, 3 kV DC. The train has different names. It is also referred to as SMILE and Gotthardzug. There are plenty of screens and information, but also unnecessary details and gimmicks. Because of invited guests and the press who used mostly the first class compartments, I could not yet take photos there that show the ambience. Switzerland, May 8, 2019. (1/31)

Because of invited guests and the press who used mostly the first class compartments, I could not yet take photos there that show the ambience. Switzerland, May 8, 2019. description:
Visiting Zürich for a few days, of course your faithful Froggish - after all, his screen name is Rana Pipiens - photographer had to go to the pretty fountain between the Predigerplatz and the Zähringerplatz. The sculpture shows a Boy with a Pennant - on which a Frog - riding a larger Frog. 
The fountain and statue date from the middle of the sixteenth century. Zürich's first printer, Christopher Froschauer (c.1490-1584) - 'Frosch' means 'Frog' in German - based himself in Zürich in 1515. Soon he was printing important works of well-known and later famous humanists and theologians, among whom Erasmus of Rotterdam, Martin Luther and Ulrich Zwingli. His establishment was quite successful and he was able to buy himself and his company a house and shop in central Zürich. He found the water supply there on the meagre side, and decided he needed his own fountain. So he had this fountain constructed and topped it off by his printer's logo, that Boy riding a Frog.       
Here it is in the Golden Green Sunlight dappling shade of Linden trees.

description: Source: en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z%C3%BCrich Zürich or Zurich is the largest city in Switzerland and the capital of the canton of Zürich. It is located in north-central Switzerland at the northwestern tip of Lake Zürich. The municipality has approximately 409,000 inhabitants, the urban agglomeration 1.315 million and the Zürich metropolitan area 1.83 million. Zürich is a hub for railways, roads, and air traffic. Both Zürich Airport and railway station are the largest and busiest in the country. Permanently settled for over 2,000 years, Zürich was founded by the Romans, who, in 15 BC, called it Turicum. However, early settlements have been found dating back more than 6,400 years ago. During the Middle Ages, Zürich gained the independent and privileged status of imperial immediacy and, in 1519, became a primary centre of the Protestant Reformation in Europe under the leadership of Huldrych Zwingli. The official language of Zürich is German, but the main spoken language is the local variant of the Alemannic Swiss German dialect, Zürich German. Many museums and art galleries can be found in the city, including the Swiss National Museum and the Kunsthaus. Schauspielhaus Zürich is one of the most important theatres in the German-speaking world. Zürich is a leading global city and among the world's largest financial centres despite having a relatively small population. The city is home to a large number of financial institutions and banking companies. Most of Switzerland's research and development centres are concentrated in Zürich and the low tax rates attract overseas companies to set up their headquarters there. Monocle's 2012 "Quality of Life Survey" ranked Zürich first on a list of the top 25 cities in the world "to make a base within". According to several surveys from 2006 to 2008, Zürich was named the city with the best quality of life in the world as well as the wealthiest city in Europe in terms of GDP per capita. The Economist Intelligence Unit's Global Liveability Ranking sees Zürich rank among the top ten most liveable cities in the world.

description: Source: en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z%C3%BCrich Zürich or Zurich is the largest city in Switzerland and the capital of the canton of Zürich. It is located in north-central Switzerland at the northwestern tip of Lake Zürich. The municipality has approximately 409,000 inhabitants, the urban agglomeration 1.315 million and the Zürich metropolitan area 1.83 million. Zürich is a hub for railways, roads, and air traffic. Both Zürich Airport and railway station are the largest and busiest in the country. Permanently settled for over 2,000 years, Zürich was founded by the Romans, who, in 15 BC, called it Turicum. However, early settlements have been found dating back more than 6,400 years ago. During the Middle Ages, Zürich gained the independent and privileged status of imperial immediacy and, in 1519, became a primary centre of the Protestant Reformation in Europe under the leadership of Huldrych Zwingli. The official language of Zürich is German, but the main spoken language is the local variant of the Alemannic Swiss German dialect, Zürich German. Many museums and art galleries can be found in the city, including the Swiss National Museum and the Kunsthaus. Schauspielhaus Zürich is one of the most important theatres in the German-speaking world. Zürich is a leading global city and among the world's largest financial centres despite having a relatively small population. The city is home to a large number of financial institutions and banking companies. Most of Switzerland's research and development centres are concentrated in Zürich and the low tax rates attract overseas companies to set up their headquarters there. Monocle's 2012 "Quality of Life Survey" ranked Zürich first on a list of the top 25 cities in the world "to make a base within". According to several surveys from 2006 to 2008, Zürich was named the city with the best quality of life in the world as well as the wealthiest city in Europe in terms of GDP per capita. The Economist Intelligence Unit's Global Liveability Ranking sees Zürich rank among the top ten most liveable cities in the world.

description:
Zurich Bahnhofstrasse and Paradeplatz (home to the Swiss banks Credit Suisse and UBS and several Zurich prime shops) remain a no-go-area for participants of the official labour day rally at Bürkiplatz (the far end of Bahnhofstrasse, at lake Zurich). 
Zurich metro police blocks all passages to Bahnhofstrasse and Paradeplatz. Phalanx like single and double rows of officers in riot gear span across the streets. Facing Bürkliplatz, a mobile water cannon is in position on Bahnhofstrasse.

Zurich May Day, 2010

description:
Two Zurich metro police officers check a homeless near Zurich main railway station (Hauptbahnhof).

I wasn't prepared for night photography, so first I had to get the flash to work. 
The homeless is behind the officer to the right. The constable to the left is searching the possessions of the homeless, and the constable to the right (wearing a jacket) confronted me right after I had shot the picture (he had noticed the flash). 

So, the guy came up to me with a friendly smile. He said hello and introduced himself: "Stalder's my name, you?" - "Hello Mr Stalder, Natiez", I responded. 
"I don't want to be photographed at work", he then said. I told him that I had taken only one picture so far and that one couldn't see his face on it. He then pointed his right trigger finger at the label on his jacket, above the heart region, stating "Polizei" (police), and said, "I am police. And I want you to walk on now." 
I was rather amused by his reaction. I answered, "Sir, of course you may do that, as a police officer you indeed may tell me to walk on, and I think you also call it 'circulation', so you want me to circulate?" He then nodded and went back to their victim, the homeless whose stuff they were searching.

Since I've always been a good boy and as of age 18 a good citizen, I followed the officer's order. Of course I did. 
As a result I circulated, round and round in circles... I crossed the street and walked back and forth, watching the scene from a greater distance. To remain in circulation I crossed the street a little later again. And so forth. That's true circulation.

Finally, the officers accompanied the homeless to a nearby tram station and placed him under the small side-roof of the station. This made sense because of the first rain drops falling. So the constables made sure the homeless moved from his bench (where he would have got soaked) under the roof of the nearby tram station. Well done!

Next morning, Friday October 1, I decided to go to the main station of Zurich metro police and "sort it out", once and forever.  

There was a female officer at the entrance desk. I told her the story, that her colleagues had been searching a homeless last night, the place where there are usually loads of punks. She knew where. I said I took a picture. And I told her that her comerade sent me away right away, arguing that he doesn't want to be photographed while he's doing his job. 
I told the officer that I followed the order instantly and that I don't want to mess with police. I explained to her that therefore I now need to know the photography rules precisely and once and forever. 

She answered she'd get the "Wachchef" on duty, that's the head officer on duty. She didn't know whether he'd have time, but she went to see... 

So, the "Wachchef" came within less than a minute. 

I told him the story. He answered that basically I MAY take pictures of his crew on duty ALWAYS as long as I DO NOT HINDER AN OFFICIAL ACT ("Hinderung einer Amtshandlung"), a serious offence. 
He also said that portrait pictures showing the officer's or their customer's faces weren't allowed. And concerning any more in-depth questions he referred me to Mr Cortesi, the metro police spokesman. He would kindly answer them.

I'm very thankful for the information. It's what I needed. I MAY!

Conclusions:
Being a pain in the neck I now could say that by sending me away constable Stalder abused his authority ("Amtsmissbrauch") because obviously I was not hindering an official act (I wasn't even close to them as you can see on the picture). 
Since I am not a trouble maker I won't sue him, though. Yet, a police officer has to accept that he (or she) can be framed photographically ANY TIME during work. Besides, if I was a constable, I'd be absolutely comfortable with that. Serving the public? Picture me anytime!

Further, it's rather hard to understand why or how taking pictures would hinder an official act.

On the other side, I agree that Mr Stalder and his colleagues protect the personalities of their customers. They may protect people (their victims and customers) from pictures by shielding them (take off your jacket and hold it infront of the face of the person you're searching). It isn't allowed, though, to send the photographer away, unless, of course, he (or she) is hindering an official act. 
But then, are photographers with telelenses privileged? Nope. Taking pictures, even portrait pictures, remains legal also with a 50mm lens, provided the photographer does not hinder an official act. 
As said above, I don't see how anybody could hinder an official police act by merely taking pictures. 

The privacy issue: 
Publishing pictures might lead to legal arguments, especially if people can be identified on a picture. Local laws apply, so if a picture's published under US laws it's a simple as it could get, US laws apply. :-)
Besides, as a rule, I personally photoshop pictures to protect innocent people's personalities. 
Anyway, pictures only show what happens in real life - so why should anybody be ashamed? Sh*t happens... It's the burgeois mind and the narcisstic personalities who are afraid of being shown on a photo with constables in the neck...

That's an attitude, isn't it? Well, as long as the aperture's right, it works out fine.

Both Zürich Airport and railway station are the largest and busiest in the country. Permanently settled for around 2000 years, the history of Zürich goes back to its founding by the Romans, who, in 15 BC, called it Turicum. However, early settlements have been found dating back more than 6400 years ago. During the Middle Ages Zürich gained the independent and privileged status of imperial immediacy and, in 1519, became a primary centre of the Protestant Reformation in Europe under the leadership of Ulrich Zwingli. Zürich is a leading global city and among the world's largest financial centres. The city is home to a large number of financial institutions and banking giants. Most of Switzerland's research and development centres are concentrated in Zürich and the low tax rates attract overseas companies to set up their headquarters there. description:
The Fraumunster is one of Zurich's 4 main churches, founded in the 9th century. The current owner is Evangelical Reformed Church of Zurich. 

The Fraumunster lies on the west of the Limmat River, directly opposite the Grossmunster. As their names suggest, they were men and women only many years ago.

description: Zurigo - i giardini di Lindenhof Oggi in pieno centro, Lindenhof corrisponde alla antica urbanizzazione di Turicum, risale all'epoca dell'imperatore romano Valentiniano I (364-375) la costruzione in questa zona di un castello che doveva servire a difendere la stazione doganale contro le incursioni dei popoli germanici provenienti da nord. Ora c'è una piazza alberata, luogo idilliaco da dove si gode una bellissima vista della città, grazie al fatto che si trova su un'altura sulla sponda sinistra del Limmat. Questa statua sulla fontana commemora la difesa delle donne della città nel 1291 contro Alberto I di Germania. I piccioni gradiscono ;-) Do not use any of my images on websites, blogs or other media without my explicit written permission. All rights reserved - Copyright © fotomie2009 - Nora Caracci

description:
Photo André Knoerr, Genève. Reproduction autorisée avec mention de la source.
Utilisation commerciale soumise à autorisation spéciale préalable.

*50 Jahre TMZ Tram Museum Zürich 1967-2017*
Le 20 août 2017, le TMZ a organisé une journée spéciale pour les autobus historiques.
Malgré l'éclatement de la collection qui avait fait couler beaucoup d'encre il y a quelques années, une rencontre d'autobus hébergés par divers groupements a pu être mise sur roues.
Le TMZ a récemment pris de nouveaux véhicules dans sa collection d'autobus.

Le plus ancien autobus zürichois, le Saurer V 9 (1929) arrive au Tram Museum en croisant une rame du Forchbahn avec la Be 4/6 71 en queue, lors d'une course publique.
On remarque la "flèche" levée remplaçant le clignoteur.

16567

Un seul Kim Jong c'est suffisant.
IL FAUT STOPPER Kim Jong-Deux alias Donald Trump!

description:
Wasserkirche, 1486. 

Its left part,  the Helmhaus, is an extension of the church to the north, 1791. 

The tower behind it:
Grossmünster — iconic twin-towered Romanesque cathedral, where 1500s religious reformer Huldrych Zwingli preached. 
The twin towers of the Grossmünster (we can only see one in this image) are regarded as perhaps the most recognized landmark in Zürich.  The two towers were first erected between 1487 and 1492. Originally, they had high wooden steeples, which were destroyed by fire in 1763, following which the present neo-Gothic tops were added (completed 1787).

Zurich. 2018

description:
Der Blaue Pfeilgiftfrosch ist in seiner Heimat, den Regenwaldinseln in der Sipaliwini Savanne im Grenzgebiet von Surinam und Brasilien, stark bedroht. Einerseits, weil sein Lebensraum sehr klein ist, andererseits, weil er immer noch illegal gesammelt und ausser Landes geschmuggelt wird. An der Brutpflege der Jungen beteiligen sich beide Eltern, im Terrarium gelingt die Zucht relativ leicht. Weil die Kaulquappen zum Kannibalismus neigen, ist es nötig, sie voneinander zu trennen.

Verwandtschaft: 
Amphibien, Froschlurche, Pfeilgiftfrösche 

Lebensraum: 
im relativ kühlen (22 bis 27°C) tropischen Regenwald, unter Steinen und Moos in Wassernähe, meist am Boden 

Futter: 
Gliederfüssler, überwiegend Ameisen und Termiten 

Gelegegrösse: 
2 bis 6 Eier 

Gesamtlänge: 
bis 4.5 cm 

Fortpflanzung: 
Schlupf nach etwa 14 bis 18 Tagen. Metamorphose (Umwandlung von der Kaulquappe zum Frosch) etwa 70 bis 85 Tage später.
tags: bysäne frösche frogs blau blue azur dendrobatesazureus blauerpfeilgiftfrosch dendrobateazure dentrobateazuro bluepoisonfrog zürichzoo schweiz amphibien amphibians picnik

description: Please don't use this image on websites, blogs or other media without my written permission. © Toni_V. All rights reserved. Der neue Durchgangsbahnhof Löwenstrasse unterquert die Sihl. Deshalb musste auch unter der Sihl ein Deckel eingezogen werden. Dazu wurde der Fluss unterhalb des Hauptbahnhofes abschnittsweise trockengelegt. Mit Baugeräten, die unter der Brücke Platz fanden, wurden Hilfswände und ﻿2014Pfähle in den Untergrund getrieben, damit der Deckel betoniert werden konnte. Seit Mai 2011 fliesst die Sihl wieder in ihrem natürlichen Flussbett. Unterhalb des erstellten Deckels wurde anschliessend der Untergrund für den Bahnhof Löwenstrasse ausgehoben. Die Kosten für den Durchgangsbahnhof Löwenstrasse belaufen sich auf knapp 660 Millionen Franken.

description:
Our Lady's Church in Zurich is a Roman Catholic parish church in the main city of Zurich. She stands at nine in the quarter Zehnderweg Unterstrass.

description: Breaking The News by Marc Lee www.tweakfest.ch/festival/2007/program/program_detail_de.... Tweakfest, the Festival for Media Culture & Digital Lifestyle, will take place in the Technopark, Puls 5 and Schiffsbau area of Zurich West from 24 to 26 May 2007. Tweakfest is the first platform to combine culture, research, communication, and entertainment. As such it brings together all the actors in Switzerland's up-and-coming creative economy. The Tweakfest offers creative spirits, researchers and managers a forum in which to debate and make presentations. This year, the specialist conference will comprise international keynote speeches, round table discussions, question-and-answer sessions, break-out sessions, workshops, plus showcase and/or prototype presentations by innovative Swiss research labs and companies. Besides the conference, once again the full range of digital creativity will be there for visitors to experience, including exhibitions of Web art and research projects; a trade show for home electronics and digital accessories; an interactive metaverse, software, and Web 2.0 laboratory; a media art performance; screenings of mobile and digital films; and a club area with parties featuring electronic DJ's, VJ's, and live acts plus artists' workshops and demonstrations of creative tools. www.macprime.ch/tweakfest
tags: tweakfest 2007 zurich wozniak stevewozniak keynote speech technology media culture mediaculture digitallifestyle digital lifestyle technopark puls5 schiffsbau research communication festival swiss switzerland canon eos 350d

description:
Two weeks ago I spent the day in Zürich. The sun showed itself from its best side, so that I could make a few wonderful photos including also the sunset over Zürich. But that very special event took place on this river called „Limmat“. 

Imagine … here is held every year at this season a fun swimming. It is called the „Samichlausschwimmen“ in Swiss German and I would say it means something like „Santa Claus Swimming“ :-) Well, about 330 people dared at temperatures of 6 degrees (water) and 3 degrees (air) to take a swim in the river Limmat. And unlike last year, this time no snow fell ;-))

And there they stood all the swimmer and waited for their turn to jump into this river. Some of them even dressed up as Santa Claus and jumped with a loud „Ho ho ho!“ into the cold water, only to emerge with a cry (I think this water was very cold this year) (lol). It was really a magnificent spectacle :-)

Well, maybe you want to see how this event looked like? That’s why I have posted two additional images! To see them just klick on the link below to show all comments. I have posted the two images in the first two comments. I hope you like it :-)

I want to thank all very much for your "views", "Comments" and "Favourites" :-) The only thing that matters is that you have joy in this photo. Again, thank you :-)

description: The Museum of Design, Zürich is a museum for industrial design, visual communication, architecture, and craft in Zurich, Switzerland. The new Toni Campus is a vision come true - bringing all the disciplines in arts and design together in an extraordinary location. The site is a former dairy factory, whose closure made way for cutting-edge clubs like the Toni Molkerei or the Dachkantine. It set a cultural tone with epoch-making events and art exhibitions, now serving as a base for the Zurich University of the Arts.

description:
I'm not much of a portrait photographer, that is I rarely do it, because I somehow feel as if intruding on people. What better place to start, then, than with oneself. Incidentally, I'm also camera-shy. How convenient that I can hide behind my hair :-)
This one works best in black&white. I don't remember what I thought of in that exact moment, but my face looks genuinely happy.

description: Gli bastava uno sguardo al campanile per saperlo ;-) Zurigo - Fraumunster (serie) È insieme al Grossmünster la chiesa più importante di Zurigo. Le due chiese si affacciano dalle rispettive sponde del fiume Limmat, che divide il centro storico in due parti. Il Fraumünster si trova sulla riva sinistra, ossia quella occidentale. È ora un tempio protestante. La chiesa si basa su una costruzione eretta in epoca carolingia. Il suo impianto attuale è legato prevalentemente all'architettura gotica. Tuttavia, vi sono importanti elementi romanici come i tre finestroni in seguito decorati da Marc Chagall: essi costituiscono uno dei maggiori elementi decorativi della chiesa, nel complesso abbastanza spoglia come vuole la tradizione zwingliana. Anche solo queste vetrate meritano la visita... Poiché all'interno della chiesa non si potevano scattare foto, perciò vi mostro la scannerizzazione di una cartolina che riproduce un particolare di una vetrata. ------------ Do not use any of my images on websites, blogs or other media without my explicit written permission. All rights reserved - Copyright © fotomie2009 - Nora Caracci

description: Short visit to Zurich and Schaffhausen waterfalls Signature-Origin demonstrated successfully in Zurich Zürich or Zurich (/ˈzjʊərɪk/ ZEWR-ik) is the largest city in Switzerland and the capital of the canton of Zürich. It is located in north-central Switzerland[3] at the northwestern tip of Lake Zürich. The municipality has approximately 400,028[4] inhabitants, the urban agglomeration 1.315 million[5] and the Zürich metropolitan area 1.83 million.[6] Zürich is a hub for railways, roads, and air traffic. Both Zürich Airport and railway station are the largest and busiest in the country. Permanently settled for over 2000 years, Zürich was founded by the Romans, who, in 15 BC, called it Turicum. However, early settlements have been found dating back more than 6400 years ago.[7] During the Middle Ages, Zürich gained the independent and privileged status of imperial immediacy and, in 1519, became a primary centre of the Protestant Reformation in Europe under the leadership of Huldrych Zwingli.[8] The official language of Zürich is German,[a] but the main spoken language is the local variant of the Alemannic Swiss German dialect. Many museums and art galleries can be found in the city, including the Swiss National Museum and the Kunsthaus.[9] Schauspielhaus Zürich is one of the most important theatres in the German-speaking world.[10] Zürich is a leading global city and among the world's largest financial centres despite having a relatively small population.[11] The city is home to a large number of financial institutions and banking companies. Most of Switzerland's research and development centres are concentrated in Zürich and the low tax rates attract overseas companies to set up their headquarters there. Monocle's 2012 "Quality of Life Survey" ranked Zürich first on a list of the top 25 cities in the world "to make a base within".[12] According to several surveys from 2006 to 2008, Zürich was named the city with the best quality of life in the world as well as the wealthiest city in Europe in terms of GDP per capita.[13][14][15] The Economist Intelligence Unit's Global Liveability Ranking[16] sees Zürich rank among the top ten most liveable cities in the world. en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z%C3%BCrich

description: Please don't use this image on websites, blogs or other media without my written permission. © Toni_V. All rights reserved. Der neue Durchgangsbahnhof Löwenstrasse unterquert die Sihl. Deshalb musste auch unter der Sihl ein Deckel eingezogen werden. Dazu wurde der Fluss unterhalb des Hauptbahnhofes abschnittsweise trockengelegt. Mit Baugeräten, die unter der Brücke Platz fanden, wurden Hilfswände und ﻿2014Pfähle in den Untergrund getrieben, damit der Deckel betoniert werden konnte. Seit Mai 2011 fliesst die Sihl wieder in ihrem natürlichen Flussbett. Unterhalb des erstellten Deckels wurde anschliessend der Untergrund für den Bahnhof Löwenstrasse ausgehoben. Die Kosten für den Durchgangsbahnhof Löwenstrasse belaufen sich auf knapp 660 Millionen Franken.

Die Durchmesserlinie von Altstetten–Zürich nach HB–Oerlikon (DML) ist ein Schweizer Eisenbahnprojekt zur direkten Verbindung der Bahnhöfe Altstetten und Oerlikon durch den unter dem Zürcher Hauptbahnhof gelegenen zweiten Tiefbahnhof Löwenstrasse. Die Strecke ist 9,6 Kilometer lang, und umfasst neben dem neuen viergleisigen Tiefbahnhof, die 1156 Meter lange Letzigrabenbrücke, die 394 Meter lange Kohlendreieckbrücke, sowie den knapp 5 Kilometer langen Weinbergtunnel. Der Tiefbahnhof ist zudem an die linksufrige Seebahn nach Thalwil angeschlossen. Der Zusammenschluss mit der oberirdischen Zufahrt in den Bahnhof Oerlikon erfolgt über zwei zusätzliche Gleise im Oerliker Einschnitt, welche bis in den Bahnhof hinein reichen. Nicht zum Projekt gehört der Ausbau des Bahnhof Oerlikon, welcher zwar von der DML beeinflusst, aber separat geplant und finanziert wurde, und zusammen mit der Stadt Zürich bis Ende 2016 umgesetzt werden soll. Der Streckenteil zwischen dem Bahnhof Oerlikon und dem Zürcher Hauptbahnhof wurde Mitte Juni 2014 in Betrieb genommen. Die vorher im als Kopfbahnhof ausgeführten provisorischen Bahnhofsteil Sihlpost des Zürcher Hauptbahnhofs gewendeten durchgehenden S-Bahnen S2 und S8 (Anschluss nach Thalwil) und die dort beginnende und endende S14 (nach und aus Hinwil über Oerlikon) benutzen seitdem den Bahnhof Löwenstrasse und die neue Strecke bis und von Oerlikon. Fernverkehrszüge aus Richtung Aarau zur Weiterfahrt über Oerlikon in die Ostschweiz und umgekehrt werden die Durchmesserlinie erst nach Fertigstellung der beiden Brücken im Jahr 2015 befahren. ©wikipedia
